ploring Berks County, PA. I love the speed and Japan, as it clashes with the ancient traditions. I love the beauty of Paris and most of Europe. I am moving towards more extreme traveling as I get older. It\'s more about totally removing myself from other human stimulus and allowing nature to cleanse the palette.\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nAs the founder of the Luxury Brand SVSV - What are some of the luxuries in life you enjoy?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nI must admit, I prefer extremely fine cameras. I have been shooting on a Linhof, 4x5 field camera lately and loving it. I typically shoot on Leica\'s and prefer my M9 to anything else. I will be obtaining a 100 year old Graflex RB soon to shoot new portrait studies. Other than that, I prefer nice cars and motorcycles and lots of travel.\n\nI love collecting art, but only things that speak to me personally, so much of my art is from friends or strange things I find in obscure antique stores and flea markets. I typically avoid what many would consider \"traditional\" forms of luxury. I think ultimately, being able to disconnect from work and the chaos of New York and spend time with my wife and family is the best luxury.\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nWhat\'s would be the best advice you could give someone in the design/entrepreneurial world?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nAvoid the hype and drama and focus on the mechanics and building a strong foundation. Education is the best investment you can ever make - so invest heavily in yourself and you will never regret it. Also, trends and fads pass, so focus on the deeper meaning of things and the bigger ideas that stand the test of time.','DAVID GENSLER','','inherit','open','open','','69-autosave','','','2012-03-26 11:06:28','2012-03-26 18:06:28','',69,'http://spiraldesign.ca/69-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(153,1,'2012-03-11 09:27:23','2012-03-11 16:27:23','','Interview Custom Fields','','inherit','open','open','','acf_interview-custom-fields-16','','','2012-03-11 09:27:23','2012-03-11 16:27:23','',31,'http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/acf_interview-custom-fields-16/',0,'revision','',0),(159,2,'2012-03-11 15:48:40','2012-03-11 22:48:40','','interview-p-brodie-gunning','','inherit','open','open','','interview-p-brodie-gunning','','','2012-03-11 15:48:40','2012-03-11 22:48:40','',102,'http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/interview-p-brodie-gunning.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(160,2,'2012-03-22 13:25:21','2012-03-22 20:25:21','<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/interview-image-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"325\" height=\"434\" /></div>\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nWhere did you grow up?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nI was born in Baltimore, Maryland. I lived there until I was in the 4th grade, then moved to Berks County, Pennsylvania. I have lived in California several times in my life, Colorado, Philadelphia and now call Brooklyn, New York home.\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nHow did you first get into design and business?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nI was always more interested in what was behind the scenes, than what was on the surface. This curiosity to discover has lead me down an alternative and rewarding road. I started my formal education in Photography, then shifted to Industrial Design and Advertising. My affinity for writing opened doors for me in business and strategy, which lead me back to business school to focus on marketing and strategy. You put all those things together and you have a wide array of tools to help you build and manage brands. Most recently I have once again shifted to intense studies in digital strategy and before that fashion design. Always stay in a constant state of learning and growing - otherwise you will lose your competitive edge.\n<blockquote class=\"right\">“I was always more interested in what was behind the scenes, than what was on the surface.”</blockquote>\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nWho are your day to day partners at The KDU and SVSV and what are their specific rolls?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nI have some amazing people who surround me and make things happen. Jared Liner is my Creative Director and day to day studio manger partner. He holds the studio together in regards to projects and clients. My wife, Margarita also handles operations and is who I feel most comfortable putting in front of press and sales for SVSV. Josh Vanover, while not based in Brooklyn is a partner who leads the “art” side of the army. His work is pushing the cutting edge right now and brings me the most inspiration.\n<div><img class=\"left\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/interview-image-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nYou have so many things going on at the moment, what are the most recent developments of SVSV?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nWe are be working hard to expand our in-house factory. We named the factory, Brooklyn Sewn and it has been an amazing and rewarding experience. We are also trying to get back to our roots with more avant garde work to balance the more contemporary work we have been producing lately - the trick is finding the balance between both worlds.\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\nThe KDU is growing daily with new designers, can you tell us about them?\n<h3 class=\"answer\">David:</h3>\nEach designer, artists or creative professional is hand selected by me personally. People are recommended from other members and colleagues, but the ultimate selection process is determined by me alone. I want the KDU to continue to stand in opposition to mass, technology driven platform and crowd sourcing collectives - the only way to truly avoid this is to know each member personally, having an intimate understanding of their portfolios, work styles and flow.','Brodie Gunning','','inherit','open','open','','102-autosave','','','2012-03-22 13:25:21','2012-03-22 20:25:21','',102,'http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/102-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(71,1,'2012-03-04 08:46:43','2012-03-04 08:46:43','','Interview Custom Fields','','inherit','open','open','','acf_interview-custom-fields-6','','','2012-03-04 08:46:43','2012-03-04 08:46:43','',31,'http://spiraldesign.ca/acf_interview-custom-fields-6/',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2012-03-04 08:50:58','2012-03-04 08:50:58','<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop.tumblr-2.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"360\" height=\"540\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"caption right\" style=\"width: 360px;\">Afternoon light in Soho</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nYou’re now living and working in NYC, where are you from originally and what brought you to NYC?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nAbout a year and a half ago New York photographer Christian Oth skyped me one day in my Whale Beach treehouse (Sydney, Australia) - he told me to get a haircut and come and shoot for him. Couldn\'t say no. His tight-knit team of photogs are all legends in their own fields but come together under the \'<a title=\"Christian Oth Studio NYC\" href=\"http://www.christianothstudio.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Christian Oth Studio</a>\' banner to document New York &amp; destination weddings.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nHow did you get started in Photography and when did you decide it was what you wanted to do for a living?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nI started shooting when my dad got sick 7 years ago. Due to brain damage brought on by meningococcal he now has no short term or picture memory and is legally blind. This is essentially what photography is for me - it\'s seeing stuff and creating memories, often optimistically.\r\n\r\nIt took me a while to figure out that I could shoot for a living. I was working a boring office job but I had the advantage of having a generous boss who gave me flexibility to shoot when I had shoots and work for him when I wasn\'t shooting. It came to a point where I had too many shoots to turn around and no time to work in the office so that was that.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat style of photography do you specialize in and what are you looking to expand into?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nI find this a tough question because at a glance I guess some would say I\'m a wedding photographer... but wedding photography, at least good wedding photography, encompasses a range of skills or \"styles\". You need to take on the role of a photojournalist, a fashion shooter, a portrait photographer, a detail/editorial shooter, an interiors photographer, a party photog &amp; be able to get all this within a very limited amount of time. On top of that you’re working with real people, not models! So you\'ve got to think fast and shoot even faster. You\'ve also got to have people skills if the experience is going to be bearable for the client.\r\n\r\nAt the end of the day I believe you need to bring your own creativity &amp; personality to whatever it is you\'re shooting, which is hard to box as one particular style.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">I have been shooting more and more street photography since moving to New York and that’s something I’ll definitely continue. Most days I will take one lens out and simply wander the streets of Manhattan, looking for stuff. It’s amazing what you begin to see when you start looking. Particularly in a city like this.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class=\"right\">“Be nice. Don\'t burn people. Be yourself (unless of course you normally burn people in which case don\'t be yourself, just be someone nice).”</blockquote>\r\n<img class=\"left\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-street1.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"333\" height=\"500\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption left\">Olivia Wilde on the street</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nYou photograph luxury cars as you see them on the streets of NYC... what\'s your current top 5 list of luxury cars?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nYeah there\'s so many nice cars here it\'s insane. In fact, the other day I witnessed a twenty-something year old leave my local brooklyn coffee shop and get into his gunmetal grey V10 Audi R8. I didn\'t know whether to cheer or cry. I used to drive an Audi Avant in Sydney so I always love seeing RS5\'s, RS4 Avants, R8\'s and all their siblings on the streets. Rolls Ghost\'s are fair epic too just when you start thinking about the cost of them and the possibility of who\'s in them. That\'s four. Black Ferrari\'s are also just plain rad. I shot a black Ferrari 458 the other week. That was cool.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nYour dream client/s?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nMy dream clients are ones who book me for me. They \"get\" what I do and trust me to see what I see and do what I do. Hopefully Audi or A.P.C will call me soon. Ha. Actually I\'d definitely do contra for Leica too.\r\n<h3 class=\"question clear-left\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWho are some of the photographers you have had the opportunity to work with and who would you like to work with in the future?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">Working with Christian Oth Studio has given me the privilege of shooting alongside and learning from some incredible photographers. I often feel completely out of my league, which is a good place to be. Christian brings a full on creative-fashion-vogue angle to weddings making brides look drop dead gorgeous and he has a unique way of mixing this up with a magnum-esque photojournalists approach. Sometimes I shoot with Mike Falco - he comes from a hardcore NYTimes photojournalism background, and still shoots for the Times - his ability to tell a whole story in one or two pictures is truly a gift.</p>\r\n<img class=\"full-width\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-fullwidth-image.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption full-width\">Bicycle | Brooklyn | Blue</div>\r\nGuy Calaf has a similar thing going on but with an unmatched Italian-Australian-New York intensity. Other days I\'ll be shooting alongside Shawn Connell - he is a phenomenal detail shooter &amp; the way he sees and reads the light continually blows me away. Meredith Davenport is an award winning National Geographic photographer and so on and so on... It\'s starting to read like a PR piece, I know, but I am genuinely so stoked to be working alongside these photographers as they are all legends in their fields and so down-to-earth and yet we all shoot weddings. I think that\'s so cool.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">If you asked me a year ago who I would like to work with in the future then I wouldn\'t have been able to name any of the names I just mentioned. I don\'t really have a list of who\'s who that I want to work with. It\'s often the unknowns that are so fun &amp; inspiring to work with moreso than the big personalities.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class=\"full-width line-2 line-2-after\">“It’s amazing what you begin to see when you start looking. Particularly in a city like this.”</blockquote>\r\n<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-audi.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"427\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"caption right\">Audi A8L in the Meat Packing District</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat is your current set up and what\'s on the wish list?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer clear-left\">Glen:</h3>\r\nHere\'s the list:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>5DmkII</li>\r\n	<li>5D (the original still use this guy cos the colour is just awesome on skin tones. ask any professional photo editor. And the feel of the shutter is this awesome old school \'clunk\'.)</li>\r\n	<li>85mm f1.2 (the fave)</li>\r\n	<li>50mm f1.2</li>\r\n	<li>24-70mm f2.8</li>\r\n	<li>70-200mm f2.8 II (\"the sniper\"... far out this guy is so heavy)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n...and then a few flashes and bits and pieces you know, all in my (now heavy) Billingham 550.\r\nI also shoot 35mm film on a Leica Minilux and an ancient beaten up Canon A2.\r\n\r\nOn the wish list is for Canon to bring out a 35mm f1.2. The 35mm 1.4 is beautiful, but f1.2 is f1.2 and I have this inkling that the moment I buy the f1.4 they\'ll announce the 1.2 and I\'ll be instantly jealous. A lot of readers may not understand that sentence, sorry. Ha. Whilst we\'re on the wish list wagon I\'d throw in a Leica Noctilux 50mm f0.95 (the quickest way to spend $11K) and a Leica M7. Please.\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nDo you have any advice to give fellow photographers looking to expand their client base?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nWell... I just think if you do a great job and over-deliver then there\'s a better chance you\'ll get a referral. And from referrals come more referrals and so on. Be nice. Don\'t burn people. Be yourself (unless of course you normally burn people in which case don\'t be yourself, just be someone nice).\r\n<h3 class=\"question\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat are some of your favourite locations to shoot?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nI\'ve had some amazing opportunities particularly since working for Christian. The first week I got here Christian sat me down and asked if I was ok to go shoot a wedding in Switzerland in 2 weeks time (\"umm yes\"). That was epic. Besides that we shot a wedding party that went rafting in Jackson Hole Wyoming, an on-stage wedding in a massive old theatre in Texas, a bushfire-smoke-filled few days in Georgia amongst the hanging mossy trees, sunset on the beach in the Hamptons, a lobster picnic dinner for 250 guests in Martha\'s Vineyard... yeah we\'ve seen some amazing stuff.\r\n<p class=\"spacer\">One of my old favourites though is a little place right on the water in Palm Beach, Sydney, called \"The Boathouse\". Sea planes come in and out, the food is perfectly Australian, the atmosphere super relaxed, the sunset is so peaceful and the staff are way too nice to call them \'staff\'. I used to shoot a lot there and that\'s one of the locations I miss the most in Sydney.</p>\r\n<img class=\"full-width\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-fullwidth-image2.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<div class=\"caption full-width\">(L) Commuters (R) Malibu wedding</div>\r\n<h3 class=\"question clear-left\">Asher:</h3>\r\nWhat are some of the best things about being a photographer?\r\n<h3 class=\"answer\">Glen:</h3>\r\nShooting. I just love shooting. Some days I love it because of the people I meet, some days its the opportunity to shoot something ridiculously amazing, other days I just like the feel of the shutter under my finger, other days its the delayed gratification of not knowing what the picture\'s going to look like until I take another 35 shots to finish the roll and then get it developed. I love it all and wouldn\'t trade it for anything.','GLEN ALLSOP','','publish','closed','closed','','glen-allsop','','','2012-03-29 17:14:08','2012-03-30 00:14:08','',0,'http://spiraldesign.ca/?post_type=interview&#038;p=72',0,'interview','',0),(170,1,'2012-03-19 08:16:34','2012-03-19 15:16:34','','redskins','','inherit','open','open','','redskins-2','','','2012-03-19 08:16:34','2012-03-19 15:16:34','',72,'http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/redskins1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(122,1,'2012-03-08 06:09:12','2012-03-08 06:09:12','','interview-image-2','','inherit','open','open','','interview-image-2','','','2012-03-08 06:09:12','2012-03-08 06:09:12','',72,'http://spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/interview-image-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(74,1,'2012-04-04 19:59:01','2012-04-05 02:59:01','<div><img class=\"right\" src=\"http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop.tumblr-2.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"360\" height=\"540\" /></div>\n<div class=\"caption right\" style=\"width: 360px;\">Afternoon light in Soho</div>\n<h3 cla